We recommended that the management:
Revisit the agency’s Physical Inventory Plan to address issues encountered during previous inventory activities that hindered the efficient and effective conduct of the physical count;
Continue and expedite the conduct of a complete physical count of all PPE to ensure accuracy and completeness;
Strengthen coordination between the Accounting and Property Units to ensure simultaneous updates of PPE acquisitions, transfers, and disposal;
Implement a system or database that allows both offices to access and update records in real time, reducing discrepancies going forward; and
Utilize inventory forms prescribed by COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, and ensure that asset details such as location, condition, and user are properly recorded

We reiterated our recommendation that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Accountant to:

Review the accounts with negative balances, determine its causes and make necessary adjustments to establish the correct and normal balances of liabilities;

Use the proper financial accounts in recognizing and classifying transactions; 


Adjust the unreleased commercial checks to the appropriate accounts as at year-end and thereafter, for the ensuing year, make proper entries upon release of checks and receipt of payees;

Prepare an aging schedule for all liabilities;




Re-evaluate the claims and require submission of proper documents, otherwise in the absence of supporting documents to support the basis of payment or settlement, derecognize the liabilities; and

Ensure that all liabilities are existing and bonafide obligations of the LGU and consistent with the recognition principles under IPSAS 1.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the following:

Municipal Engineer 
accomplish the Program of Works for the projects of 20% DF before the preparation of the Annual Budget;

expedite the unimplemented 20% DF projects and ensure the timely completion of the 20% DF projects;

Municipal Planning and Development Officer

Coordinate with the Engineering Office and specify the expected start date and completion dates of the PPA of 20% DF in the Annual Investment Plan for the concrete basis of other work plans;

Evaluate the technical viability of proposed development projects before appropriation is requested in order to optimize the 20% DF;

Monitor and evaluate the implementation of projects and ensure the adherence to plans, targets and performance indicators;

The Municipal Engineer and Local Finance Committee prepare the Quarterly Physical Report of Operations and Physical and Financial Performance Evaluation Form, respectively, for them to assess the plans, conditions, situations, and targets of projects of 20% DF; and

The Municipal Budget Officer assists the Municipal Engineer in the preparation of the required reports stated in the BOM for LGU.

We recommended that the management;


Before undertaking projects by administration, consider to review the capacity and capability of the municipality to undertake such projects considering the available technical resources as well as the manpower and equipment necessary to implement the projects;

Refrain from implementing multiple projects simultaneously to avoid delays on the completion of the project so as not to defer the benefits to stakeholders of the project;

Prepare the Quarterly Report on Government Projects/Programs/Activities by attaching supporting documents as basis such as Statement of Work Accomplished (SWA) and Subsidiary Ledger (SL) to properly determine the actual physical accomplishment and actual total cost incurred as of a given date for each project.

We recommended that the management to;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and submit subsidiary schedules of general ledger accounts and Statement of Appropriations, Allotments, Obligations and Balances (SAAOB) (Annex E) to serve as basis in the review of the financial statements.

Investigate the negative/abnormal balances of various identified accounts and make necessary adjusting entries thereof.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

Impose the required expanded withholding tax on the succeeding payments to the professionals, consultants, other recipients of talent fees, rental of personal properties, and suppliers of services, except, when the annual income is below the threshold of P250,000.00 and upon submission of Income Payee’s Sworn Declaration of Gross Receipts/Sales;

Adhere to the above provisions, rules, and regulations.

We recommend that the Municipal Mayor require the following officers:

Municipal Human Resource Management Officer

Submit the Daily Time Records (DTR) of all personnel for CY 2022, unaccounted Certificate of Attendance of Regular Sessions of Sanggunian Bayan and its attachment for the application for leave and official travel, if applicable;

Evaluate the DTR and summarize the absences, undertime, and tardiness of each personnel for CY 2022 and submit the same;

Deduct the absences and undertime/tardiness of personnel for the calendar year 2022 and the absences during regular sessions of Sangguniang Bayan Officials from the calendar year 2019 to 2022 and the following years to their cumulative earned leave credits;

Require all personnel to submit on time and attach all supporting documents related to their absences or official travel, if necessary, to the Daily Time Records that are to be submitted to the Accounting Office for proper evaluation of deduction of leave credits and payment of salaries; and

Municipal Accountant

Examine the daily time record, certificate of attendance during regular sessions – for Sangguniang Bayan Members, approved applications for leave and other documents related to the official business/travel of personnel and officials and use as basis in the preparation of payrolls for the payment of their salaries and attached these documents to the payrolls; and

Ensure the completeness of supporting documents to be attached to the payroll.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Require all offices, through the Department Heads to accomplish the Inventory Count Form and submit the same to the Inventory Committee for their verification before the conduct of actual inventory of the Inventory Committee;
Direct the Inventory Committee to:
plan/strategize on how to conduct and complete the physical inventory and prepare Physical Inventory Plan (PIP);
submit the approved PIP to the Audit team at least ten (10) calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory taking activities;
prepare and submit the Report on Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) upon completion of the physical count;
Enforce both the Accounting and Supply Office to update their records and reports and to coordinate with the Inventory Committee in order to reconcile the inventory count with their reports;
Strictly require the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer to resolve all the variances noted between their reports;
Enjoin all concerned officials and employees to comply with the procedures laid out in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Accountant to:
Review the accounts with negative balances, determine its causes and make necessary adjustments to establish the correct and normal balances of liabilities;
Use the proper financial accounts in recognizing and classifying transactions;
Adjust the unreleased commercial checks to the appropriate accounts as at year-end and thereafter, for the ensuing year, make proper entries upon release of checks and receipt of payees;
Prioritize settling the outstanding inter-agency liabilities by remitting the amounts withheld to the proper recipient government agencies and ensure that the remittances to the BIR and Pag-IBIG are proper and will not result to overpayments;
Prepare an aging schedule for all liabilities;
Re-evaluate the claims and require submission of proper documents, otherwise in the absence of supporting documents to support the basis of payment or settlement, derecognize the liabilities; and
Ensure that all liabilities are existing and bonafide obligations of the LGU and consistent with the recognition principles under IPSAS 1.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require:
The Accountable Officers from the Requesting/Receiving Office to submit a certified list of Recipients with their actual receipt, unless circumstances may justify absence of actual receipt;
The General Services Officer to -
Prepare the forms prescribed by the Manual with supporting documents from the accountable officers and ensure submission to Accounting Office promptly to effect actual issuance to recipients and recognize any unissued stocks;
Conduct physical count of Inventories and prepare the RPCI with sufficient and relevant details;
The Municipal Accountant to recognize the Inventory following the Perpetual Inventory Method and ensure that issuance and any balances, if any, are properly accounted in the books; and
The General Services Officer and Municipal Accountant to conduct regular reconciliation of the inventories to ensure the fair presentation of the inventory accounts.

We recommended the Management to ensure that:

a) Cash balances in the bank accounts of the LGU are properly accounted and reconciled with the cashbook and book balances;

b) The Municipal Accountant maintain a special account in the General Fund for the 20% Economic Development Fund and that separate subsidiary ledgers and financial statements should be prepared;

c) Stale checks as well as unreleased checks are properly adjusted as at year-end;

d) All adjustments against the cash accounts shall be supported with proper documents;

e) Reconciliation between the Accounting, Budget and Treasury Offices is undertaken regularly; and

f) Cash accounts are monitored consistently and should be presented fairly in accordance with IPSAS 1 and other accounting rules and regulations.

We recommended the following corrective actions:

a) The Management should ensure that the LDRRMFIP includes projects, plans and activities that shall be charged against the unexpended prior years’ balances;

b) The Municipal Mayor to instruct the Municipal Treasurer to transfer the CY 2020 unexpended balances of LDRRMF to the Calamity Fund bank account in the Trust Fund;

c) The Municipal Accountant should make the proper and necessary journal entries in accounting all LDRRMF transactions both in the General Fund books and Trust Fund books; and

d) All concerned officials should submit the LDRRMF Investment Plan with details on prior years’ unexpended balances, Inventory reports and other pertinent documents and to strictly comply with the accounting and reporting guidelines as prescribed by the above-cited rules and regulations.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require:

a) The Inventory Committee and the General Services Officer to conduct annual physical count of all the properties of the LGU and to render a more comprehensive and accurate Report on Physical Count of PPE;

b) The Municipal Accountant to apply consistently the recognition principle in recording PPE and effect proper entries for the noted errors/misstatements and recognize corresponding depreciation expenses, if proper; 

c) Semestral reconciliation between the Accounting and General Services Office in order that any differences in their records will be properly addressed;

 d) The Municipal Accountant to keep up-to-date such ledgers and other schedules and the General Services Officer to update the system and inventory reports in order that proper reconciliation may be undertaken with more reliable reports; and

e) Compliance by all concerned official with the aforementioned rules and regulations.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

a) Require both the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to perform regular reconciliation of accounting records with the cash book to immediately address and account for any discrepancies thereat;

b) Improve cash management to avoid incurrence of cash deficits and assertively pursue feasible solutions that will address the issue involving fiscal operations of the Municipality;

c) Undertake to reactivate immediately the status of the Calamity Fund account which became dormant and instruct the Municipal Accountant to transfer all the unexpended LDRRMF balances as well as other receipts of donations into the said account in order to establish exclusively the use of such account for LDRRM;

d) Cause the Municipal Treasurer to prepare the Reports of Checks Issued with complete details and indicate as well all the spoiled, stale or cancelled checks thereto in order to facilitate easy monitoring of said checks; and

e) Require strict compliance by the responsible officials with the reportorial requirements as prescribed by the above-cited rules and regulations.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:

a) Fully account for the P11.494M trust funds and identify the sources of these funds in order that the same be returned accordingly;

b) Return all the unexpended funds transfers to the concerned Source Agencies and/or remit the same immediately to the National Treasury, as required by the afore-cited rules and regulations.

We recommended the following:

a) The GAD Focal Person and members of the Technical Working Group use monitoring tools such as the HGDG and PIMME in monitoring and evaluating GAD activities and submit to the Audit Team the annual accomplishment report for evaluation;

b) Utilization of the GAD budget should be in accordance with the DILG-endorsed GAD Plan and Budget, GAD laws, rules and regulations.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

a) Require the MDRRMC to prepare the LDRRMFIP by adopting the prescribed format in the Annex A of the COA Circular 2012-002, review and update annually the LDRRMFIP to include activities to be funded from the unexpended QRF and DRRMF-MOOE of the previous years which were transferred to the Special Trust Fund;

b) Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and certify correct the monthly report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF using the prescribed format in Annex B of this Circular;

c) Direct the MDRRO to submit to the Auditor the report on or before 15th day after the end of each month through the LDRRMC and Local Development Council (LDC).

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require:

a) The concerned personnel of the Inventory Committee and Supply Office to conduct physical inventory taking into consideration the appropriate timing, planning and coordination among all offices; 

b) The Accounting and Supply Office to update and reconcile their records in order to ascertain the accuracy, existence and accountability of all PPE items;

c) The Inventory Committee, in coordination with the Supply and Accounting Office to establish a set of inventory guidelines and provide information dissemination to all LGU officers and employees concerning the reporting, disposal and all other processes involving PPE in order that the Supply Office and/or Accounting Office will be kept well-informed of all PPE transactions and take proper action.

