b) The management should specify the details of programs, projects and activities to be funded by the LDRRM Fund and efficiently implement the specific programs, projects and activities that are laid out in the LDRRMP and AIP or to its supplemental or revised plans, if any;

c) The Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer should ensure that receipts of funds specifically for calamity purposes must be accounted in the Trust Liability – DRRM in the Trust Fund books;

d) The Management should give priority for the inclusion of appropriation for stockpiling of disaster risk reduction equipment and other basic emergency supplies; and

e) The Management adhere with all the rules and regulations laid out relative to LDRRM Fund.

We recommended Management to:

a) Strictly utilize the Quick Response Fund supported with a duly approved Declaration of State of Calamity stating thereat the specific criteria as enumerated in NDRRMC Memorandum Order No. 60, s. 2019 dated June 17, 2019 and using the format prescribed in NDRRMC Memorandum Circular No.  25, s. 2014;

b) Efficiently implement programs, projects and activities that are within the LDRRMP and AIP or to its supplemental or revised plans, if any, and make sure that details as to projects and activities to be funded are specified on the Plan;
c) Require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Budget Officer to reconcile their reports to establish the correct balances of the Fund;

d) Instruct the Municipal Accountant to recognize the transactions into the appropriate accounts and make a reconciliation thereof; and

e) Strictly and prudently comply with all the rules and regulations laid out relative to LDRRM Fund.

We recommended that:

a) The Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Assessor and Municipal Treasurer to reconcile their records to come up with a complete and more accurate list showing the name of the taxpayers with the amounts due and collectible which shall be used as basis in setting up the correct Real Property Tax and Special Education Tax Receivables by the Municipal Accountant;

b) The Local Chief Executive should also require the Office of the Local Assessor to conduct tax mapping operations to make possible the establishment of a property record system that is easily adapted to data computerization. Tax mapping operations are essential in the establishment of an adequate real property tax record and accounting system.

c) The Municipal Accountant should set up RPT/SET Receivables at the beginning of the year based on a duly certified list of taxpayers and the amounts due and collectible for the year prepared by the Municipal Treasurer and account for all related RPT/SET transactions to achieve fair presentation of the affected accounts in the Financial Statements;

d) The Municipal Accountant ensure that demandable taxes and collections thereof be accounted properly in the RPT/SET Receivables and any delinquent accounts be continuously reported in the books unless subsequently settled;

e) The Municipal Treasurer avail of remedies and formulate strategies provided under the Rules and Regulations Implementing the Local Government Code of 1991 to improve, intensify and properly enforce collection of RPT/SET; and

f) The concerned officials adhere strictly to the above-stated law and rules.

We recommended that:

a) The concerned officials ascertain and resolve the discrepancies noted between the books and physical inventory, update their records and documents which pertain to the receipt, issuance and disposal of PPE and enforce a regular reconciliation between the Accounting and Supply Office in order to address the noted differences in their reports;

b) The Municipal Accountant should set-up provisions for the depreciation and impairment losses of PPE and provide sufficient disclosures of PPE accounts in the financial statements consistent with PPSAS 17.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

